# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cowboy-jones
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cowboy-jones/1898-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1898 throughout the world.
[src:cowboy-jones/1901-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1901 throughout the world.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:cowboy-jones/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The **Cleveland Spiders** were an American professional baseball team based in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The team competed at the major league level from 1887 to 1899, first for two seasons as a member of the now-defunct American Association (AA), followed by eleven seasons in the National League (NL).
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Early names for the team included the **Forest Citys** and **Blues**.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The name Spiders itself emerged early in the team's inaugural NL season of 1889, owing to new black-and-gray uniforms and the skinny, long-limbed look of many players (thereby resembling the spider).
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] National League Park served as the team's home for its first four seasons until the opening of League Park in 1891.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Amid seven straight winning seasons under manager Patsy Tebeau, the team finished second in the National League three times – in 1892, 1895, and 1896.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] While the Spiders never won the National League pennant, the club did win the 1895 Temple Cup, a two-team league championship playoff predating the World Series.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders beat that year's pennant winner, the Baltimore Orioles (unrelated to the modern franchise), four games to one in a best-of-seven game series.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Six Spiders players were later inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, including left fielder Jesse Burkett and pitcher Cy Young.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] In 1899, owners Frank and Stanley Robison purchased a second team – the bankrupt St.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Louis NL franchise – and sent all of the Spiders' top talent to that club, including future Hall-of-Famers Young, Burkett, and Bobby Wallace.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The resulting Spiders roster finished the 1899 season 20–134, a record which remains the worst for a single season in major league history.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were subsequently one of four teams contracted by the National League that year.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Partly in response to the Robison brothers' actions – which effectively ended the Spiders franchise – the practice of "syndicate ownership" was later banned.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis played for the team during its final three seasons and is often credited as the first Native American to play major league baseball.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians, major league successor to the Spiders in Cleveland, have long cited Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – though that claim is disputed.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were the third professional baseball franchise based in Cleveland.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The first team, Forest City, which played from 1870 through 1872, was initially an independent team before joining the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for two seasons before disbanding.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] They were followed in 1879 by the city's first National League team, the Cleveland Blues, which folded after the 1884 season.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] After the 1886 season, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys left the American Association (AA) to join the National League.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The AA, then considered a major league, chose the Cleveland group headed by Frank Robison as an expansion team to begin play in 1887 over proposals from Kansas City and Detroit.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Later, Robison's brother Stanley was added to the ownership group.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Initially, the team was known as the Forest Citys, drawing on the city's nickname and the nickname that had been used on the city's two previous professional baseball teams.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The nickname Blues was also used again in reference to the team uniforms.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Forest Citys were a weak team in their early years.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] In 1889, they moved to the National League and became known as the Spiders, reportedly after comments from a team executive assessing the players.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Brunell, this team executive who also doubled as sportswriter for *The Plain Dealer*, noted the combination of the team's new black-and-gray uniforms together with the sight of several skinny, long-limbed players.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] He joked the team should be called "Spiders", and the name stuck.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The team started to improve in 1891, largely due to the signing of future Baseball Hall of Fame pitcher Cy Young.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders had their first taste of success in 1892 when they finished 93–56 overall; winning the second half by three games over Boston with a 53–23 record.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Other than standout second baseman Cupid Childs, the Spiders had an unremarkable offense.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Their success in 1892 was built on pitching strength; Cy Young was the NL's most dominant hurler, and 22-year-old George Cuppy had an outstanding rookie year.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Following the season, a "World's Championship Series" exhibition was played between Cleveland and the first-half winner Boston Beaneaters, but the Spiders could only muster one tie in six games.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] In 1895, the Spiders again finished second, this time to the equally rough-and-tumble Baltimore Orioles.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Young again led the league in wins, and speedy left fielder Jesse Burkett won the batting title with a .409 average.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders won the Temple Cup, an 1890s postseason series between the first- and second-place teams in the NL.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Amid fan rowdyism and garbage-throwing, the Spiders won four of five games against Baltimore, including two wins for Cy Young.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The 1895 championship was the high-water mark for the franchise.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The following season, Baltimore and Cleveland again finished first and second in the NL, but in the battle for the 1896 Temple Cup, the second-place Spiders were swept in four games.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] In 1897, despite a winning record, the franchise finished fifth, a season highlighted by Young throwing the first of three career no-hitters on September 18.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders again finished fifth in 1898.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] In 1899, the Spiders' owners, the Robison brothers, bought the St.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Louis Browns out of bankruptcy and changed their name to the Perfectos.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] However, they kept the Spiders as well—a blatant conflict of interest.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Believing the Perfectos would draw greater attendance in more densely populated St.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Louis, the Robisons transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Baseball Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, to St.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] They also shifted a large number of Cleveland home games to the road (for instance, the original Opening Day game was shifted to St.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] With a decimated roster, the Spiders made a wretched showing.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] They finished with a dismal win-loss record of 20–134 (.130), the worst in MLB history, 84 games behind the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas and 35 games behind the next-to-last (11th) place Washington Senators.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Their batting records were the worst in the league in runs, hits, doubles, triples, home runs, walks, stolen bases, on-base percentage, and slugging percentage.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons announced after buying the Perfectos that they intended to run the Spiders as a "sideshow", and Cleveland fans apparently took them at their word.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders' first 16 home games drew a total of 3,179 fans, or an average of 199 fans per game.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Due to these meager attendance figures, the other 11 NL teams refused to come to League Park, as their cut of the revenue from ticket sales did not even begin to cover their hotel and travel expenses.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were thus forced to play 85 of their remaining 93 games on the road.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Counting the large number of home games that had been shifted to the road earlier in the season, they only played 42 home games during the season, including only eight after July 1, and finished 9–33 (.214) at home and 11–101 (.098) on the road.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Only 6,088 fans paid to attend Spiders home games in 1899, for a pitiful average of a mere 145 spectators per game in 9,000-seat League Park.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The 101 road losses is a major-league record that will never be threatened, as current scheduling practices have teams play a maximum of 81 away games.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20–21.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The 1962 New York Mets, 40–120 (.250), and the 2024 Chicago White Sox, 41–121 (.253), own the modern records in their respective leagues for the most losses, and thus draw frequent comparisons to the 1899 Spiders for futility.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons' decision to effectively reduce the Spiders to minor league status, along with other intra-league raiding such as that conducted by the Dodgers and to a lesser extent the Pittsburgh Pirates, unwittingly helped pave the way to the National League's loss of its major league monopoly.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The 12th-place Spiders were one of four teams contracted out of the National League at the end of the 1899 season (the others were the 11th-place Senators, the ninth-place Louisville Colonels and the bankrupt fourth-place Baltimore Orioles).
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The 1899 fiasco played a role in the major leagues passing a rule which barred one person from owning controlling interest in two clubs.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons sold the assets of the Spiders team to Charles Somers and John Kilfoyle in 1900.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] In 1900, the then-minor American League (previously the Western League) moved the Grand Rapids (baseball) team in to take the Spiders' place, and called the Cleveland Lake Shores.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] In 1901, after the American League declared major league status, the team was called the Cleveland Blues, eventually the Cleveland Indians, and now the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians have long claimed Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – in use from 1915 to 2021.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] Sockalexis played three seasons for the Cleveland Spiders, from 1897 to 1899, and is often credited as the first Native American to play professional baseball at the major league level.
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] During his time with the Spiders, the press often referred to the team as the Indians or "Tebeau's Indians".
[src:cowboy-jones/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians claim has been disputed, however, including in a 2012 *Cleveland Scene* essay titled "The Curse of Chief Wahoo", which argues the organization cited Sockalexis in part to justify use of the "Indians" name.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The region has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly much longer.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains was a major migration route for early peoples who spread throughout the Americas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1848, much of the Nuevo México region was annexed to the United States with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Pike's Peak Gold Rush of 1858–1862 created an influx of settlers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On February 28, 1861, U.S. president James Buchanan signed an act creating the Territory of Colorado, and on August 1, 1876, president Ulysses S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Grant signed Proclamation 230, admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Denver is the capital, the most populous city, and the center of the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado Springs is the second-most populous city of the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Residents of the state are known as Coloradans, although the antiquated "Coloradoan" is occasionally used.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado generally ranks as one of the top U.S. states for education attainment, employment, and healthcare quality.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Major parts of its economy include government and defense, mining, agriculture, tourism, and manufacturing.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] With increasing temperatures and decreasing water availability, Colorado's agriculture, forestry, and tourism economies are expected to be heavily affected by climate change.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The region that is today the State of Colorado has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly more than 37,000 years.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Lindenmeier site contains artifacts dating from approximately 8720 BCE.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Ancient Pueblo peoples lived in the valleys and mesas of the Colorado Plateau in far southwestern Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Ute Nation inhabited the mountain valleys of the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Western Rocky Mountains, even as far east as the Front Range of the present day.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Apache and the Comanche also inhabited the Eastern and Southeastern parts of the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In the 17th century, the Arapaho and Cheyenne moved west from the Great Lakes region to hunt across the High Plains of Colorado and Wyoming.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The U.S. acquired the territorial claim to the eastern Rocky Mountains with the Louisiana Purchase from France in 1803.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Army reconnaissance expedition into the disputed region.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colonel Pike and his troops were arrested by Spanish cavalrymen in the San Luis Valley the following February, taken to Chihuahua, and expelled from Mexico the following July.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Under the 1819 Adams-Onís Treaty, the U.S. acquired Florida from Spain while relinquishing claims to lands west of the 100th meridian and south of both the Arkansas River and the 42nd parallel.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The treaty took effect on February 22, 1821.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Having settled its border with Spain, the U.S. admitted the southeastern portion of the Territory of Missouri to the Union as the state of Missouri on August 10, 1821.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The remainder of Missouri Territory, including what would become northeastern Colorado, became an unorganized territory and remained so for 33 years over the question of slavery.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] After 11 years of war, Spain finally recognized the independence of Mexico with the Treaty of Córdoba signed on August 24, 1821.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Mexico eventually ratified the Adams–Onís Treaty in 1831.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Texian Revolt of 1835–36 fomented a dispute between the U.S. and Mexico which eventually erupted into the Mexican–American War in 1846.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Mexico surrendered its northern territory to the U.S. with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo after the war in 1848; this included much of the western and southern areas of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Santa Fe Trail connected the Missouri River to Santa Fe, New Mexico, where it linked with the Camino Real de Tierra Adentro extending southward into Mexico.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Others traveling overland avoided the rugged Southern Rocky Mountains, and instead followed the North Platte River and Sweetwater River to South Pass (Wyoming), the lowest crossing of the Continental Divide between the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Central Rocky Mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1849, the Mormons of the Salt Lake Valley organized the extralegal State of Deseret, claiming the entire Great Basin and all lands drained by the rivers Green, Grand, and Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The federal government of the U.S. flatly refused to recognize the new Mormon government because it was theocratic and sanctioned plural marriage.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Instead, the Compromise of 1850 divided the Mexican Cession and the northwestern claims of Texas into a new state and two new territories, the state of California, the Territory of New Mexico, and the Territory of Utah.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Provisional Government of the Territory of Jefferson was an extralegal and unrecognized United States territory that existed in the Pike's Peak mining region from October 24, 1859, until it yielded to the new Territory of Colorado on June 6, 1861.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Jefferson Territory included all of the present State of Colorado and portions of the present states of Kansas, Nebraska, Utah, and Wyoming.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The people were desirous of a closer government than those five territories provided.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The government of the Jefferson Territory, while democratically elected, was never legally recognized by the United States government, although it managed the territory with relatively free rein for 19 months.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Many of the laws enacted by the General Assembly of the Territory of Jefferson were reenacted and given official sanction by the new Colorado General Assembly in 1861.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Territory of Colorado was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from February 28, 1861, until August 1, 1876, when it was admitted to the Union as the 38th State of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The territory was created during the onset of the American Civil War in the wake of the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, which brought the first large concentration of settlers from the east to the region.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The war stifled growth, but following the war mining grew more industrialized and fueled the economy.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The construction of railroads further improved the economy.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The boundaries of the newly designated Colorado Territory were very similar to those of the modern State of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1861 following the beginning of the American Civil War, there were several small disputes and skirmishes between confederate supporters and union supporters.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In August, Governor Gilpin organized the 1st Colorado Infantry.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Slough led the group to New Mexico Territory in February–March 1862.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] There they fought in the battles of Apache Canyon, Glorieta Pass and Peralta.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Slough resigned in April 1862 and was replaced by Major John M.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] With resources tied up in the war there was little left over for mines, farms, and infrastructure, and Denver stagnated.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On March 26, 1862 John Evans was appointed by Abraham Lincoln as the second governor of the territory.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] He prompted investment in Denver rail projects, and founded the University of Denver in 1864.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Anti-native sentiment grew during the Civil War years.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Exterminationist ideology, led in Colorado by Evans and Chivington, advocated for the total eradication of all native people in the territory.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Colorado War worsened relations with natives until 1864 when Chivington ordered the Sand Creek Massacre and Evans was forced to resign the following spring.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1867, the Union Pacific Railroad laid its tracks west to Weir, now Julesburg, in the northeast corner of the Territory.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Union Pacific linked up with the Central Pacific Railroad at Promontory Summit, Utah, on May 10, 1869, to form the First transcontinental railroad.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Denver Pacific Railway reached Denver in June of the following year, and the Kansas Pacific arrived two months later to forge the second line across the continent.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The United States Congress passed an enabling act on March 3, 1875, specifying the requirements for the Territory of Colorado to become a state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On August 1, 1876 (four weeks after the Centennial of the United States), U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Grant signed a proclamation admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state and earning it the moniker "Centennial State".
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The discovery of a major silver lode near Leadville in 1878 triggered the Colorado Silver Boom.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Sherman Silver Purchase Act of 1890 invigorated silver mining, and Colorado's last, but greatest, gold strike at Cripple Creek a few months later lured a new generation of gold seekers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado women were granted the right to vote on November 7, 1893, making Colorado the second state to grant universal suffrage and the first one by a popular vote (of Colorado men).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The repeal of the Sherman Silver Purchase Act in 1893 led to a staggering collapse of the mining and agricultural economy of Colorado, but the state slowly and steadily recovered.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Between the 1880s and 1930s, Denver's floriculture industry developed into a major industry in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] This period became known locally as the Carnation Gold Rush.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Both the 1913–1914 Coalfield War and the Denver streetcar strike of 1920 resulted in federal troops intervening to end the violence.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1927, the 1927-28 Colorado coal strike occurred and was ultimately successful in winning a dollar a day increase in wages.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] During it however the Columbine Mine massacre resulted in six dead strikers following a confrontation with Colorado Rangers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In a separate incident in Trinidad the mayor was accused of deputizing members of the KKK against the striking workers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] More than 5,000 Colorado miners—many immigrants—are estimated to have died in accidents since records were first formally collected following an 1884 accident in Crested Butte that killed 59.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1924, the Ku Klux Klan Colorado Realm achieved dominance in Colorado politics.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] With peak membership levels, the Second Klan levied significant control over both the local and state Democrat and Republican parties, particularly in the governor's office and city governments of Denver, Cañon City, and Durango.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] A particularly strong element of the Klan controlled the Denver Police.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Cross burnings became semi-regular occurrences in cities such as Florence and Pueblo.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Klan targeted African-Americans, Catholics, Eastern European immigrants, and other non-White Protestant groups.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Efforts by non-Klan lawmen and lawyers including Philip Van Cise led to a rapid decline in the organization's power, with membership waning significantly by the end of the 1920s.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado became the first western state to host a major political convention when the Democratic Party met in Denver in 1908.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] By the U.S. census in 1930, the population of Colorado first exceeded one million residents.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado suffered greatly through the Great Depression and the Dust Bowl of the 1930s, but a major wave of immigration following World War II boosted Colorado's fortune.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Tourism became a mainstay of the state economy, and high technology became an important economic engine.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The United States Census Bureau estimated that the population of Colorado exceeded five million in 2009.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On September 11, 1957, a plutonium fire occurred at the Rocky Flats Plant, which resulted in the significant plutonium contamination of surrounding populated areas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] From the 1940s and 1970s, many protest movements gained momentum in Colorado, predominantly in Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] This included the Chicano Movement, a civil rights, and social movement of Mexican Americans emphasizing a Chicano identity that is widely considered to have begun in Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The National Chicano Youth Liberation Conference was held in Colorado in March 1969.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1967, Colorado was the first state to loosen restrictions on abortion when governor John Love signed a law allowing abortions in cases of rape, incest, or threats to the woman's mental or physical health.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Many states followed Colorado's lead in loosening abortion laws in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Since the late 1990s, Colorado has been the site of multiple major mass shootings, including the Columbine High School massacre in 1999, where high school senior students Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 13 students and one teacher, before committing suicide.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The incident made international news, and has since spawned many copycat incidents, known as the Columbine effect.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On July 20, 2012, a gunman killed 12 people in a movie theater in Aurora.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The state responded with tighter restrictions on firearms, including introducing a limit on magazine capacity.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On March 22, 2021, a gunman killed 10 people, including a police officer, in a King Soopers supermarket in Boulder.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In an instance of anti-LGBT violence, a gunman killed 5 people at a nightclub in Colorado Springs during the night of November 19–20, 2022.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Navy have been named the USS *Colorado*.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The first USS *Colorado* was named for the Colorado River and served in the Civil War and later the Asiatic Squadron, where it was attacked during the 1871 Korean Expedition.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The later three ships were named in honor of the state, including an armored cruiser and the battleship USS *Colorado*, the latter of which was the lead ship of her class and served in World War II in the Pacific beginning in 1941.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] At the time of the attack on Pearl Harbor, the battleship USS *Colorado* was located at the naval base in San Diego, California, and thus went unscathed.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The most recent vessel to bear the name USS *Colorado* is Virginia-class submarine USS *Colorado* (SSN-788), which was commissioned in 2018.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado is notable for its diverse geography, which includes alpine mountains, high plains, deserts with huge sand dunes, and deep canyons.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 1861, the United States Congress defined the boundaries of the new Territory of Colorado exclusively by lines of latitude and longitude, stretching from 37°N to 41°N latitude, and from 102°02′48″W to 109°02′48″W longitude (25°W to 32°W from the Washington Meridian).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] After 165 years of government surveys, the borders of Colorado were officially defined by 697 boundary markers and 697 straight boundary lines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado, Wyoming, and Utah are the only states that have their borders defined solely by straight boundary lines with no natural features.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The southwest corner of Colorado is the Four Corners Monument at 36°59′56″N, 109°2′43″W.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument, located at the place where Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah meet, is the only place in the United States where four states meet.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Approximately half of Colorado is flat and rolling land.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] East of the Rocky Mountains is the Colorado Eastern Plains of the High Plains, the section of the Great Plains within Colorado at elevations ranging from roughly 3,350 to 7,500 feet (1,020 to 2,290 m).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Colorado plains are mostly prairies but also include deciduous forests, buttes, and canyons.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Precipitation averages 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado is presently mainly farmland and rangeland, along with small farming villages and towns.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Corn, wheat, hay, soybeans, and oats are all typical crops.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Most villages and towns in this region boast both a water tower and a grain elevator.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Irrigation water is available from both surface and subterranean sources.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Surface water sources include the South Platte, the Arkansas River, and a few other streams.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Subterranean water is generally accessed through artesian wells.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Heavy usage of these wells for irrigation purposes caused underground water reserves to decline in the region.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado also hosts a considerable amount and range of livestock, such as cattle ranches and hog farms.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] About 84% of Colorado's population resides along the eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains in the Front Range Urban Corridor between Cheyenne, Wyoming, and Pueblo, Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] This region is partially protected from prevailing storms that blow in from the Pacific Ocean region by the high Rockies in the middle of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The "Front Range" includes Denver, Boulder, Fort Collins, Loveland, Castle Rock, Colorado Springs, Pueblo, Greeley, and other townships and municipalities in between.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On the other side of the Rockies, the significant population centers in western Colorado (which is known as "The Western Slope") are the cities of Grand Junction, Durango, and Montrose.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] To the west of the Great Plains of Colorado rises the eastern slope of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Notable peaks of the Rocky Mountains include Longs Peak, Mount Blue Sky, Pikes Peak, and the Spanish Peaks near Walsenburg, in southern Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] This area drains to the east and the southeast, ultimately either via the Mississippi River or the Rio Grande into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Rocky Mountains within Colorado contain 53 true peaks and 58 named peaks that are 14,000 feet (4,267 m) or higher in elevation above sea level, known as fourteeners.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] These mountains are largely covered with trees such as conifers and aspens up to the tree line, at an elevation of about 12,000 feet (3,658 m) in southern Colorado to about 10,500 feet (3,200 m) in northern Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Above this tree line, only alpine vegetation grows.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Much of the alpine snow melts by mid-August except for a few snow-capped peaks and a few small glaciers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Colorado Mineral Belt, stretching from the San Juan Mountains in the southwest to Boulder and Central City on the front range, contains most of the historic gold- and silver-mining districts of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The 30 highest major summits of the Rocky Mountains of North America are all within the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The summit of Mount Elbert at 14,437.6 feet (4,400.58 m) elevation in Lake County is the highest point in Colorado and the Rocky Mountains of North America.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Colorado is the only U.S. state that lies entirely above 1,000 meters elevation.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The point where the Arikaree River flows out of Yuma County, Colorado, and into Cheyenne County, Kansas, is the lowest in Colorado at 3,317 feet (1,011 m) elevation.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] This point, which is the highest low elevation point of any state, is higher than the high elevation points of 18 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Continental Divide of the Americas extends along the most of the crest of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The area of Colorado to the west of the Continental Divide is called the Western Slope of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] West of the Continental Divide, water flows to the southwest via the Colorado River and the Green River towards the Gulf of California.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Within the interior of the Rocky Mountains are several large parks which are high broad basins.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In the north, on the east side of the Continental Divide is the North Park of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The North Park is drained by the North Platte River, which flows north into Wyoming and Nebraska.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Just to the south of North Park, but on the western side of the Continental Divide, is the Middle Park of Colorado, which is drained by the Colorado River.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The South Park of Colorado is the region of the headwaters of the South Platte River.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In south-central Colorado is the large San Luis Valley, where the headwaters of the Rio Grande are located.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The northern part of the valley is the San Luis Closed Basin, an endorheic basin that helped created the Great Sand Dunes.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The valley sits between the Sangre de Cristo Mountains and San Juan Mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Rio Grande drains due south into New Mexico, Texas, and Mexico.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Across the Sangre de Cristo Range to the east of the San Luis Valley lies the Wet Mountain Valley.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] These basins, particularly the San Luis Valley, lie along the Rio Grande rift, a major geological formation of the Rocky Mountains, and its branches.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado includes the western face of the Rocky Mountains and all of the area to the western border.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] This area includes several terrains and climates from alpine mountains to arid deserts.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes many ski resort towns in the Rocky Mountains and towns west to Utah.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] It is less populous than the Front Range but includes a large number of national parks and monuments.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The northwestern corner of Colorado is a sparsely populated region, and it contains part of the noted Dinosaur National Monument, which not only is a paleontological area, but is also a scenic area of rocky hills, canyons, arid desert, and streambeds.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Here, the Green River briefly crosses over into Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado is drained by the Colorado River and its tributaries (primarily the Gunnison River, Green River, and the San Juan River).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Colorado River flows through Glenwood Canyon, and then through an arid valley made up of desert from Rifle to Parachute, through the desert canyon of De Beque Canyon, and into the arid desert of Grand Valley, where the city of Grand Junction is located.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Also prominent is the Grand Mesa, which lies to the southeast of Grand Junction; the high San Juan Mountains, a rugged mountain range; and to the north and west of the San Juan Mountains, the Colorado Plateau.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Grand Junction, Colorado, at the confluence of the Colorado and Gunnison Rivers, is the largest city on the Western Slope.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Grand Junction and Durango are the only major centers of television broadcasting west of the Continental Divide in Colorado, though most mountain resort communities publish daily newspapers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is located at the juncture of Interstate 70 and US 50, the only major highways in western Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is also along the major railroad of the Western Slope, the Union Pacific.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] This railroad also provides the tracks for Amtrak's *California Zephyr* passenger train, which crosses the Rocky Mountains between Denver and Grand Junction.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes multiple notable destinations in the Colorado Rocky Mountains, including Glenwood Springs, with its resort hot springs, and the ski resorts of Aspen, Breckenridge, Vail, Crested Butte, Steamboat Springs, and Telluride.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Higher education in western and southwestern Colorado includes Colorado Mesa University in Grand Junction, Western Colorado University in Gunnison, Fort Lewis College in Durango, and Colorado Mountain College campuses in Glenwood Springs and Steamboat Springs.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument in the southwest corner of Colorado marks the common boundary of Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah, the only such place in the United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The climate of Colorado is more complex than states outside of the Mountain States region.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Unlike most other states, southern Colorado is not always warmer than northern Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Most of Colorado is made up of mountains, foothills, high plains, and desert lands.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Mountains and surrounding valleys greatly affect the local climate.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Northeast, east, and southeast Colorado are mostly the high plains, while Northern Colorado is a mix of high plains, foothills, and mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Northwest and west Colorado are predominantly mountainous, with some desert lands mixed in.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Southwest and southern Colorado are a complex mixture of desert and mountain areas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The climate of the Eastern Plains is semi-arid (Köppen climate classification: *BSk*) with low humidity and moderate precipitation, usually from 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually, although many areas near the rivers are semi-humid climate.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The area is known for its abundant sunshine and cool, clear nights, which give this area a great average diurnal temperature range.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The difference between the highs of the days and the lows of the nights can be considerable as warmth dissipates to space during clear nights, the heat radiation not being trapped by clouds.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Front Range urban corridor, where most of the population of Colorado resides, lies in a pronounced precipitation shadow as a result of being on the lee side of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In summer, this area can have many days above 95 °F (35 °C) and often 100 °F (38 °C).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On the plains, the winter lows usually range from 25 to −10 °F (−4 to −23 °C).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] About 75% of the precipitation falls within the growing season, from April to September, but this area is very prone to droughts.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Most of the precipitation comes from thunderstorms, which can be severe, and from major snowstorms that occur in the winter and early spring.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Otherwise, winters tend to be mostly dry and cold.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In much of the region, March is the snowiest month.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] April and May are normally the rainiest months, while April is the wettest month overall.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Front Range cities closer to the mountains tend to be warmer in the winter due to Chinook winds which warm the area, sometimes bringing temperatures of 70 °F (21 °C) or higher in the winter.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The average July temperature is 55 °F (13 °C) in the morning and 90 °F (32 °C) in the afternoon.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The average January temperature is 18 °F (−8 °C) in the morning and 48 °F (9 °C) in the afternoon, although variation between consecutive days can be 40 °F (4 °C).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Just west of the plains and into the foothills, there is a wide variety of climate types.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Locations merely a few miles apart can experience entirely different weather depending on the topography.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Most valleys have a semi-arid climate, not unlike the eastern plains, which transitions to an alpine climate at the highest elevations.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Microclimates also exist in local areas that run nearly the entire spectrum of climates, including subtropical highland (*Cfb/Cwb*), humid subtropical (*Cfa*), humid continental (*Dfa/Dfb*), Mediterranean (*Csa/Csb*) and subarctic (*Dfc*).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Extreme weather changes are common in Colorado, although a significant portion of the extreme weather occurs in the least populated areas of the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Thunderstorms are common east of the Continental Divide in the spring and summer, yet are usually brief.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Hail is a common sight in the mountains east of the Divide and across the eastern Plains, especially the northeast part of the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Hail is the most commonly reported warm-season severe weather hazard, and occasionally causes human injuries, as well as significant property damage.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The eastern Plains are subject to some of the biggest hail storms in North America.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Notable examples are the severe hailstorms that hit Denver on July 11, 1990, and May 8, 2017, the latter being the costliest ever in the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Eastern Plains are part of the extreme western portion of Tornado Alley; some damaging tornadoes in the Eastern Plains include the 1990 Limon F3 tornado and the 2008 Windsor EF3 tornado, which devastated a small town.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Portions of the eastern Plains see especially frequent tornadoes, both those spawned from mesocyclones in supercell thunderstorms and from less intense landspouts, such as within the Denver convergence vorticity zone (DCVZ).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The Plains are also susceptible to occasional floods and particularly severe flash floods, which are caused both by thunderstorms and by the rapid melting of snow in the mountains during warm weather.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Notable examples include the 1965 Denver Flood, the Big Thompson River flooding of 1976 and the 2013 Colorado floods.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Hot weather is common during summers in Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The city's record in 1901 for the number of consecutive days above 90 °F (32 °C) was broken during the summer of 2008.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The new record of 24 consecutive days surpassed the previous record by almost a week.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Much of Colorado is very dry, with the state averaging only 17 inches (430 mm) of precipitation per year statewide.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The state rarely experiences a time when some portion is not in some degree of drought.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The lack of precipitation contributes to the severity of wildfires in the state, such as the Hayman Fire of 2002.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Other notable fires include the Fourmile Canyon Fire of 2010, the Waldo Canyon Fire and High Park Fire of June 2012, and the Black Forest Fire of June 2013.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Even these fires were exceeded in severity by the Pine Gulch Fire, Cameron Peak Fire, and East Troublesome Fire in 2020, all being the three largest fires in Colorado history (see 2020 Colorado wildfires).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] And the Marshall Fire which started on December 30, 2021, while not the largest in state history, was the most destructive ever in terms of property loss (see Marshall Fire).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] However, some of the mountainous regions of Colorado receive a huge amount of moisture from winter snowfalls.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The spring melts of these snows often cause great waterflows in the Yampa River, the Colorado River, the Rio Grande, the Arkansas River, the North Platte River, and the South Platte River.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Water flowing out of the Colorado Rocky Mountains is a very significant source of water for the farms, towns, and cities of the southwest states of New Mexico, Arizona, Utah, and Nevada, as well as the Midwest, such as Nebraska and Kansas, and the southern states of Oklahoma and Texas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] A significant amount of water is also diverted for use in California; occasionally (formerly naturally and consistently), the flow of water reaches northern Mexico.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Climate change in Colorado encompasses the effects of climate change, attributed to man-made increases in atmospheric greenhouse gases, in the U.S. state of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 2019 *The Denver Post* reported that "[i]ndividuals living in southeastern Colorado are more vulnerable to potential health effects from climate change than residents in other parts of the state".
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Most of the state has warmed one or two degrees (F) in the last century.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Throughout the western United States, heat waves are becoming more common, snow is melting earlier in spring, and less water flows through the Colorado River.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Rising temperatures and recent droughts in the region have killed many trees by drying out soils, increasing the risk of forest fires, or enabling outbreaks of forest insects.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In the coming decades, the changing climate is likely to decrease water availability and agricultural yields in Colorado, and further increase the risk of wildfires".
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The highest official ambient air temperature ever recorded in Colorado was 115 °F (46.1 °C) on July 20, 2019, at John Martin Dam.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The lowest official air temperature was −61 °F (−51.7 °C) on February 1, 1985, at Maybell.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Despite its mountainous terrain, Colorado experiences less seismic activity than states like California and Alaska.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] There are over 90 potentially active faults, and since 1867, Colorado has experienced 700 recorded earthquakes of magnitude 2.5 or higher.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] National Earthquake Information Center is located in Golden.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] On August 22, 2011, a 5.3 magnitude earthquake occurred 9 miles (14 km) west-southwest of the city of Trinidad.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] There were no casualties and only a small amount of damage was reported.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] It was the second-largest earthquake in Colorado's history, the largest being a magnitude 6.6 earthquake, recorded in 1882.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Four minor earthquakes rattled Colorado on August 24, 2018, ranging from magnitude 2.9 to 4.3.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] As of June 2020, there were 525 recorded earthquakes in Colorado since 1973, a majority of which range 2 to 3.5 on the Richter scale.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] A process of extirpation by trapping and poisoning of the gray wolf (*Canis lupus*) from Colorado in the 1930s saw the last wild wolf in the state shot in 1945.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] A wolf pack recolonized Moffat County, Colorado in northwestern Colorado in 2019.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Cattle farmers have expressed concern that a returning wolf population potentially threatens their herds.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Coloradans voted to reintroduce gray wolves in 2020, with the state committing to a plan to have a population in the state by 2022 and permitting non-lethal methods of driving off wolves attacking livestock and pets.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Despite being an artificially-introduced species, the state declared mountain goats a native species in 1993.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] In 2013, 2014, and 2019, an unknown illness killed nearly all mountain goat kids, leading to a Colorado Parks and Wildlife investigation.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The native population of pronghorn in Colorado has varied wildly over the last century, reaching a low of only 15,000 individuals during the 1960s.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] However, conservation efforts succeeded in bringing the stable population back up to roughly 66,000 by 2013.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The population was estimated to have reached 85,000 by 2019 and had increasingly more run-ins with the increased suburban housing along the eastern Front Range.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] State wildlife officials suggested that landowners would need to modify fencing to allow the greater number of pronghorns to move unabated through the newly developed land.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Pronghorns are most readily found in the northern and eastern portions of the state, with some populations also in the western San Juan Mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] Common wildlife found in the mountains of Colorado include mule deer, southwestern red squirrel, golden-mantled ground squirrel, yellow-bellied marmot, moose, American pika, and red fox, all at exceptionally high numbers, though moose are not native to the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The foothills include deer, fox squirrel, desert cottontail, mountain cottontail, and coyote.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p01] The prairies are home to black-tailed prairie dog, the endangered swift fox, American badger, and white-tailed jackrabbit.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Like the federal government and all other U.S. states, Colorado's state constitution provides for three branches of government: the legislative, the executive, and the judicial branches.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Governor of Colorado heads the state's executive branch.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The current governor is Jared Polis, a Democrat.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's other statewide elected executive officers are the Lieutenant Governor of Colorado (elected on a ticket with the Governor), Secretary of State of Colorado, Colorado State Treasurer, and Attorney General of Colorado, all of whom serve four-year terms.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The seven-member Colorado Supreme Court is the state's highest court.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Colorado Court of Appeals, with 22 judges, sits in divisions of three judges each.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado is divided into 23 judicial districts, each of which has a district court and a county court with limited jurisdiction.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state also has specialized water courts, which sit in seven distinct divisions around the state and which decide matters relating to water rights and the use and administration of water.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state legislative body is the Colorado General Assembly, which is made up of two houses – the House of Representatives and the Senate.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The House has 65 members and the Senate has 35.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] As of April 2026, the Democratic Party holds a 23 to 12 majority in the Senate and a 43 to 22 majority in the House.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] State sales taxes and many state-collected local sales taxes are administered and collected by the Colorado Department of Revenue.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado was once considered a swing state, but has become a relatively safe blue state in both state and federal elections since the late 2010s.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In presidential elections, it had not been won until 2020 by double digits since 1984 and has backed the winning candidate in 9 of the last 11 elections.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Coloradans have elected 17 Democrats and 12 Republicans to the governorship in the last 100 years.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In presidential politics, Colorado was considered a reliably Republican state during the post-World War II era, voting for the Democratic candidate only in 1948, 1964, and 1992.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] However, it became a competitive swing state in the 1990s.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Since the mid-2000s, it has swung heavily to the Democrats, voting for Barack Obama in 2008 and 2012, Hillary Clinton in 2016, Joe Biden in 2020, and Kamala Harris in 2024.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado politics exhibits a contrast between conservative cities such as Colorado Springs and Grand Junction, and liberal cities such as Boulder and Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Democrats are strongest in metropolitan Denver, the college towns of Fort Collins and Boulder, southern Colorado (including Pueblo), and several western ski resort counties.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Republicans are strongest in the Eastern Plains, Colorado Springs, Greeley, and far Western Colorado near Grand Junction.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In a 2020 study, Colorado was ranked as the seventh easiest state for citizens to vote in.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado was the first state in the union to enact, by voter referendum, a law extending suffrage to women.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] That initiative was approved by the state's voters on November 7, 1893.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On the November 8, 1932, ballot, Colorado approved the repeal of alcohol prohibition more than a year before the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution was ratified.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has banned, via C.R.S. section 12-6-302, the sale of motor vehicles on Sunday since at least 1953.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 1972, Colorado voters rejected a referendum proposal to fund the 1976 Winter Olympics, which had been scheduled to be held in the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Denver had been chosen by the International Olympic Committee as the host city on May 12, 1970.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Supreme Court found that preventing protected status based upon homosexuality or bisexuality did not satisfy the Equal Protection Clause.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2006, voters passed Amendment 43, which banned same-sex marriage in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] That initiative was nullified by the U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Supreme Court's 2015 decision in *Obergefell v.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2024, Colorado residents voted to establish an explicit right to abortion in Colorado's state constitution and to repeal Amendment 43's defunct marriage ban.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2012, voters amended the state constitution protecting the "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate cannabis like alcohol.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The first recreational marijuana shops in Colorado, and by extension the United States, opened their doors on January 1, 2014.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On October 30, 2019, Colorado became the first state to accept digital ID via its myColorado app.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state-issued digital identifications will be considered valid when Real ID enforcement begins in 2025, in line with the Real ID Act of 2005.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] By November 2022 The Colorado Governor's Office of Information Technology announced that the myColorado app had over 1 million users.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On December 19, 2023, the Colorado Supreme Court ruled that Donald Trump was disqualified from the 2024 United States presidential election in part due to his alleged incitement of the January 6 United States Capitol attack.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On March 4, 2024, the United States Supreme Court overruled the Colorado decision.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The State of Colorado is divided into 64 counties.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Two of these counties, the City and County of Broomfield and the City and County of Denver, have consolidated city and county governments.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Counties are important units of government in Colorado since there are no civil townships or other minor civil divisions.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The most populous county in Colorado is El Paso County, the home of the City of Colorado Springs.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The second most populous county is the City and County of Denver, the state capital.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Five of the 64 counties now have more than 500,000 residents, while 12 have fewer than 5,000 residents.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The ten most populous Colorado counties are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Mesa County is the most populous county on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The least populous Colorado county is Hinsdale County with 747 residents.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has 273 active incorporated municipalities, comprising 198 towns, 73 cities, and two consolidated city and county governments.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] At the 2020 United States census, 4,299,942 of the 5,773,714 Colorado residents (74.47%) lived in one of these municipalities.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Another 714,417 residents (12.37%) lived in one of the 210 census-designated places, while the remaining 759,355 residents (13.15%) lived in the many rural and mountainous areas of the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado municipalities operate under one of five types of municipal governing authority.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado currently has two consolidated city and county governments, 61 home rule cities, 12 statutory cities, 35 home rule towns, 161 statutory towns, and one territorial charter municipality.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The most populous municipality is the City and County of Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has 12 municipalities with more than 100,000 residents, and 17 with fewer than 100 residents.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The 16 most populous Colorado municipalities are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The City of Grand Junction is the most populous municipality on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Town of Carbonate has had no year-round population since the 1890 census due to its severe winter weather and difficult access.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In addition to its 272 municipalities, Colorado has 210 unincorporated census-designated places (CDPs) and many other small communities.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The most populous unincorporated community in Colorado is Highlands Ranch south of Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The seven most populous CDPs are located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Clifton CDP is the most populous CDP on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has more than 4,000 special districts, most with property tax authority.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] These districts may provide health services, ambulance, schools, law enforcement, fire protection, water, sewage, drainage, irrigation, transportation, recreation, infrastructure, cultural facilities, business support, redevelopment, or other services.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Some of these districts have the authority to levy sales tax as well as property tax and use fees.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The 17 core-based statistical areas in the U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Most recently on July 21, 2023, the Office of Management and Budget defined 21 statistical areas for Colorado comprising four combined statistical areas, seven metropolitan statistical areas, and ten micropolitan statistical areas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The most populous of the seven metropolitan statistical areas in Colorado is the 10-county Denver–Aurora–Centennial, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area with a population of 2,963,821 at the 2020 United States census, an increase of +15.29% since the 2010 census.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The more extensive 12-county Denver–Aurora–Greeley, CO Combined Statistical Area had a population of 3,623,560 at the 2020 census, an increase of +17.23% since the 2010 census.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The most populous extended metropolitan region in Rocky Mountain Region is the 18-county Front Range Urban Corridor along the northeast face of the Southern Rocky Mountains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] This region with Denver at its center had a population of 5,055,344 at the 2020 census, an increase of +16.65% since the 2010 census.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The United States Census Bureau estimated the population of Colorado on July 1, 2024, at 5,957,493, a 3.2% increase since the 2020 United States census.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Coloradan Hispanics and Latinos (of any race and heritage) made up 20.7% of the population.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] According to the 2000 census, the largest ancestry groups in Colorado are German (22%), Mexican (18%), Irish (12%), and English (12%).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Persons reporting German ancestry are especially numerous in the Front Range, the Rockies (west-central counties), and Eastern parts/High Plains.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has a high proportion of Hispanic, mostly Mexican-American, citizens in Metropolitan Denver, Colorado Springs, as well as the smaller cities of Greeley and Pueblo, and elsewhere.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Southern, Southwestern, and Southeastern Colorado have a large number of Hispanos, the descendants of the early settlers of colonial Spanish origin.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Census Bureau reported Colorado's population as 8.2% Hispanic and 90.3% non-Hispanic White.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Hispanic population of Colorado has continued to grow quickly over the past decades.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] By 2019, Hispanics made up 22% of Colorado's population, and Non-Hispanic Whites made up 70%.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Spoken English in Colorado has many Spanish idioms.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado also has some large African-American communities located in Denver, in the neighborhoods of Montbello, Five Points, Whittier, and many other East Denver areas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In the 2020 Census, 234,828 Colorado residents were identified as African American (of the total 5,773,714).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Arapahoe, at 10.8% African American, was the only one of the state's 64 counties where African Americans make up more than 10% of the population.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] African Americans in the seven counties of Arapahoe (70,787), Denver (64,038), El Paso (43,822), Adams (17,463), Jefferson (7,356), Douglas (5,160), and Weld (4,539) make up more than 90% of all African Americans in the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The population of Native Americans in the state is small.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Native Americans are concentrated in metropolitan Denver and the southwestern corner of Colorado, where there are two Ute reservations.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The majority of Colorado's immigrants are from Mexico, India, China, Vietnam, Korea, Germany and Canada.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] There were a total of 70,331 births in Colorado in 2006.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] (Birth rate of 14.6 per thousand.) In 2007, non-Hispanic Whites were involved in 59.1% of all births.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Some 14.06% of those births involved a non-Hispanic White person and someone of a different race, most often with a couple including one Hispanic.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] A birth where at least one Hispanic person was involved counted for 43% of the births in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Per the 2000 census, the Hispanic population is estimated to be 918,899, or approximately 20% of the state's total population.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has the 5th-largest population of Mexican-Americans, behind California, Texas, Arizona, and Illinois.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In percentages, Colorado has the 6th-highest percentage of Mexican-Americans, behind New Mexico, California, Texas, Arizona, and Nevada.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2011, 46% of Colorado's population younger than the age of one were minorities, meaning that they had at least one parent who was not non-Hispanic White.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2017, Colorado recorded the second-lowest fertility rate in the United States outside of New England, after Oregon, at 1.63 children per woman.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Significant contributing factors to the decline in pregnancies were the Title X Family Planning Program and an intrauterine device grant from Warren Buffett's family.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] English, the official language of the state, is the most commonly spoken language in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The second most commonly spoken language in the state is Spanish.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Colorado River Numic language, also known as the Ute dialect, is still spoken in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Major religious affiliations of the people of Colorado as of 2014 were 64% Christian, of whom there are 44% Protestant, 16% Roman Catholic, 3% Mormon, and 1% Eastern Orthodox.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Other religious breakdowns according to the Pew Research Center were 1% Judaism, 1% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, and 4% other.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Secular Coloradans made up 29% of the population.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2020, according to the Public Religion Research Institute, Christianity was 66% of the population.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Judaism was also reported to have increased in this separate study, forming 2% of the religious landscape, while the religiously unaffiliated were reported to form 28% of the population in this separate study.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2022, the same organization reported 61% was Christian (39% Protestant, 19% Catholic, 2% Mormon, 1% Eastern Orthodox), 2% New Age, 1% Jewish, 1% Hindu, and 34% religiously unaffiliated.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] According to the Association of Religion Data Archives, the largest Christian denominations by the number of adherents in 2010 were the Catholic Church with 811,630; multi-denominational Evangelical Protestants with 229,981; and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 151,433.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2020, the Association of Religion Data Archives determined the largest Christian denominations were Catholics (873,236), non/multi/inter-denominational Protestants (406,798), and Mormons (150,509).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Throughout its non-Christian population, there were 12,500 Hindus, 7,101 Hindu Yogis, and 17,369 Buddhists at the 2020 study.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Our Lady of Guadalupe Catholic Church was the first permanent Catholic parish in modern-day Colorado and was constructed by Spanish colonists from New Mexico in modern-day Conejos.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Latin Church Catholics are served by three dioceses: the Archdiocese of Denver and the Dioceses of Colorado Springs and Pueblo.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The first permanent settlement by members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Colorado arrived from Mississippi and initially camped along the Arkansas River just east of the present-day site of Pueblo.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado is generally considered among the healthiest states by behavioral and healthcare researchers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Among the positive contributing factors is the state's well-known outdoor recreation opportunities and initiatives.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] However, there is a stratification of health metrics with wealthier counties such as Douglas and Pitkin performing significantly better relative to southern, less wealthy counties such as Huerfano and Las Animas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] According to several studies, Coloradans have the lowest rates of obesity of any state in the US.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] As of 2018, 24% of the population was considered medically obese, and while the lowest in the nation, the percentage had increased from 17% in 2004.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] According to a report in the *Journal of the American Medical Association*, residents of Colorado had a 2014 life expectancy of 80.21 years, the longest of any U.S. state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 10,397 homeless people in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The number of employer establishments is 174,258.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's gross domestic product in 2025 was $584.3 billion.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's per capita personal income was $86,181 in 2025, ranking Colorado 10th in the nation.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Median Annual Household Income in 2016 was $70,666, 8th in the nation.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state's economy broadened from its mid-19th-century roots in mining when irrigated agriculture developed, and by the late 19th century, raising livestock had become important.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Early industry was based on the extraction and processing of minerals and agricultural products.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Current agricultural products are cattle, wheat, dairy products, corn, and hay.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2025, small businesses made up 99.5% of Colorado businesses, and employed 48.6% of the state's work force.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Geological Survey and other government agencies at the Denver Federal Center near Lakewood; the Denver Mint, Buckley Space Force Base, the Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals, and the Byron G.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Rogers Federal Building and United States Courthouse in Denver; and a federal Supermax Prison and other federal prisons near Cañon City.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In addition to these and other federal agencies, Colorado has abundant National Forest land and four National Parks that contribute to federal ownership of 24,615,788 acres (99,617 km2) of land in Colorado, or 37% of the total area of the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In the second half of the 20th century, the industrial and service sectors expanded greatly.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state's economy is diversified and is notable for its concentration on scientific research and high-technology industries.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Other industries include food processing, transportation equipment, machinery, chemical products, the extraction of metals such as gold (see Gold mining in Colorado), silver, and molybdenum.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado now also has the largest annual production of beer in any state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Denver is an important financial center.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state's diverse geography and majestic mountains attract millions of tourists every year, including 85.2 million in 2018.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Tourism contributes greatly to Colorado's economy, with tourists generating $22.3 billion in 2018.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Several nationally known brand names have originated in Colorado factories and laboratories.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] From Denver came the forerunner of telecommunications giant Qwest in 1879, Samsonite luggage in 1910, Gates belts and hoses in 1911, and Russell Stover Candies in 1923.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Kuner canned vegetables began in Brighton in 1864.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] From Golden came Coors beer in 1873, CoorsTek industrial ceramics in 1920, and Jolly Rancher candy in 1949.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] CF&I railroad rails, wire, nails, and pipe debuted in Pueblo in 1892.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Holly Sugar was first milled from beets in Holly in 1905, and later moved its headquarters to Colorado Springs.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The present-day Swift packed meat of Greeley evolved from Monfort of Colorado, Inc., established in 1930.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Estes model rockets were launched in Penrose in 1958.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Fort Collins has been the home of Woodward Governor Company's motor controllers (governors) since 1870, and Waterpik dental water jets and showerheads since 1962.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Celestial Seasonings herbal teas have been made in Boulder since 1969.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Rocky Mountain Chocolate Factory made its first candy in Durango in 1981.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has a flat 4.63% income tax, regardless of income level.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On November 3, 2020, voters authorized an initiative to lower that income tax rate to 4.55 percent.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Unlike most states, which calculate taxes based on federal *adjusted gross income*, Colorado taxes are based on *taxable income*—income after federal exemptions and federal itemized (or standard) deductions.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's state sales tax is 2.9% on retail sales.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] When state revenues exceed state constitutional limits, according to Colorado's Taxpayer Bill of Rights legislation, full-year Colorado residents can claim a sales tax refund on their individual state income tax return.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Many counties and cities charge their own rates, in addition to the base state rate.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] There are also certain county and special district taxes that may apply.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Real estate and personal business property are taxable in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state's senior property tax exemption was temporarily suspended by the Colorado Legislature in 2003.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The tax break was scheduled to return for the assessment year 2006, payable in 2007.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] As of May 2025, the state's unemployment rate was 4.8%.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The West Virginia teachers' strike in 2018 inspired teachers in other states, including Colorado, to take similar action.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Corn is grown in the Eastern Plains of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Arid conditions and drought negatively impacted yields in 2020 and 2022.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado has significant hydrocarbon resources.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] According to the Energy Information Administration, Colorado hosts seven of the largest natural gas fields in the United States, and two of the largest oil fields.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Conventional and unconventional natural gas output from several Colorado basins typically accounts for more than five percent of annual U.S. natural gas production.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's oil shale deposits hold an estimated 1 trillion barrels (160 km3) of oil—nearly as much oil as the entire world's proven oil reserves.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Substantial deposits of bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite coal are found in the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Uranium mining in Colorado goes back to 1872, when pitchblende ore was taken from gold mines near Central City, Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Not counting byproduct uranium from phosphate, Colorado is considered to have the third-largest uranium reserves of any U.S. state, behind Wyoming and New Mexico.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] When Colorado and Utah dominated radium mining from 1910 to 1922, uranium and vanadium were the byproducts (giving towns like present-day Superfund site Uravan their names).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Uranium price increases from 2001 to 2007 prompted several companies to revive uranium mining in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] During the 1940s certain communities–including Naturita and Paradox–earned the moniker of "yellowcake towns" from their relationship with uranium mining.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Price drops and financing problems in late 2008 forced these companies to cancel or scale back the uranium-mining project.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] As of 2016, there were no major uranium mining operations in the state, though plans existed to restart production.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's high Rocky Mountain ridges and eastern plains offer wind power potential, and geologic activity in the mountain areas provides the potential for geothermal power development.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Much of the state is sunny and could produce solar power.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Major rivers flowing from the Rocky Mountains offer hydroelectric power resources.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Several film productions have been shot on location in Colorado, especially prominent Westerns like *True Grit*, *The Searchers*, *City Slickers,* *Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid, and My Life With the Walter Boys*.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Several historic military forts, railways with trains still operating, and mining ghost towns have been used and transformed for historical accuracy in well-known films.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] There are also several scenic highways and mountain passes that helped to feature the open road in films such as *Vanishing Point*, *Bingo* and *Starman*.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Some Colorado landmarks have been featured in films, such as The Stanley Hotel in *Dumb and Dumber* and *The Shining* and the Sculptured House in *Sleeper*.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2015, *Furious 7* was to film driving sequences on Pikes Peak Highway in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The TV adult-animated series *South Park* takes place in central Colorado in the titular town.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Additionally, the TV series *Good Luck Charlie* was set, but not filmed, in Denver, Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Colorado Office of Film and Television has noted that more than 400 films have been shot in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On March 27, 2025, it was announced Sundance Film Festival would move to Boulder starting in 2027 after reaching a deal for a ten-year duration.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Many notable writers have lived or spent extended periods in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] *5280*, a Denver magazine, wrote in 2015 that Kent Haruf is "widely considered [to be] Colorado's finest novelist"; Haruf set his novels in the fictional high plains Colorado town of Holt.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Beat Generation writers Jack Kerouac and Neal Cassady lived in and around Denver for several years each.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Irish playwright Oscar Wilde visited Colorado on his tour of the United States in 1882, writing in his 1906 *Impressions of America* that Leadville was "the richest city in the world.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado is known for its Southwest and Rocky Mountain cuisine, with Mexican restaurants found throughout the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Boulder was named America's Foodiest Town 2010 by Bon Appétit.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Boulder, and Colorado in general, is home to several national food and beverage companies, top-tier restaurants and farmers' markets.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Boulder also has more Master Sommeliers per capita than any other city, including San Francisco and New York.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Denver is known for steak, but now has a diverse culinary scene with many restaurants.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Polidori Sausage is a brand of pork products available in supermarkets, which originated in Colorado, in the early 20th century.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Food & Wine Classic is held annually each June in Aspen.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Aspen also has a reputation as the culinary capital of the Rocky Mountain region.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado wines include varietals that have attracted favorable notice from outside the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] With wines made from traditional *Vitis vinifera* grapes along with wines made from cherries, peaches, plums, and honey, Colorado wines have won top national and international awards for their quality.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's grape growing regions contain the highest elevation vineyards in the United States, with most viticulture in the state practiced between 4,000 and 7,000 feet (1,219 and 2,134 m) above sea level.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The mountain climate ensures warm summer days and cool nights.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to two designated American Viticultural Areas of the Grand Valley AVA and the West Elks AVA, where most of the vineyards in the state are located.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] However, an increasing number of wineries are located along the Front Range.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 2018, Wine Enthusiast Magazine named Colorado's Grand Valley AVA in Mesa County, Colorado, as one of the Top Ten wine travel destinations in the world.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to many nationally praised microbreweries, including New Belgium Brewing Company, Odell Brewing Company, and Great Divide Brewing Company.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The area of northern Colorado near and between the cities of Denver, Boulder, and Fort Collins is known as the "Napa Valley of Beer" due to its high density of craft breweries.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado is open to cannabis (marijuana) tourism.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] With the adoption of the 64th state amendment in 2012, Colorado became the first state in the union to legalize marijuana for medicinal (2000), industrial (referring to hemp, 2012), and recreational (2012) use.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's marijuana industry sold $1.31 billion worth of marijuana in 2016 and $1.26 billion in the first three-quarters of 2017.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state generated tax, fee, and license revenue of $194 million in 2016 on legal marijuana sales.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado regulates hemp as any part of the plant with less than 0.3% THC.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On April 4, 2014, Senate Bill 14–184 addressing oversight of Colorado's industrial hemp program was first introduced, ultimately being signed into law by Governor John Hickenlooper on May 31, 2014.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On November 7, 2000, 54% of Colorado voters passed Amendment 20, which amends the Colorado State constitution to allow the medical use of marijuana.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Currently, Colorado has listed "eight medical conditions for which patients can use marijuana—cancer, glaucoma, HIV/AIDS, muscle spasms, seizures, severe pain, severe nausea and cachexia, or dramatic weight loss and muscle atrophy".
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] While governor, John Hickenlooper allocated about half of the state's $13 million "Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund" to medical research in the 2014 budget.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] By 2018, the Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund was the "largest pool of pot money in the state" and was used to fund programs including research into pediatric applications for controlling autism symptoms.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On November 6, 2012, voters amended the state constitution to protect "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate marijuana in a manner similar to alcohol.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's primary mode of transportation (in terms of passengers) is its highway system.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Interstate 25 (I-25) is the primary north–south highway in the state, connecting Pueblo, Colorado Springs, Denver, and Fort Collins, and extending north to Wyoming and south to New Mexico.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] It connects Grand Junction and the mountain communities with Denver and enters Utah and Kansas.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The state is home to a network of US and Colorado highways that provide access to all principal areas of the state.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Many smaller communities are connected to this network only via county roads.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Denver International Airport (DIA) is the third-busiest domestic U.S. and international airport in the world by passenger traffic.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] DIA handles by far the largest volume of commercial air traffic in Colorado and is the busiest U.S. hub airport between Chicago and the Pacific coast, making Denver the most important airport for connecting passenger traffic in the western United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Public transportation bus services are offered both intra-city and inter-city—including the Denver metro area's RTD services.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Regional Transportation District (RTD) operates the popular RTD Bus & Rail transit system in the Denver Metropolitan Area.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] As of January 2013 the RTD rail system had 170 light-rail vehicles, serving 47 miles (76 km) of track.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In addition to local public transit, intercity bus service is provided by Burlington Trailways, Bustang and Greyhound Lines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Amtrak operates two passenger rail lines in Colorado, the *California Zephyr* and *Southwest Chief*.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's contribution to world railroad history was forged principally by the Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad which began in 1870 and wrote the book on mountain railroading.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 1988 the "Rio Grande" was acquired, but was merged into, the Southern Pacific Railroad by their joint owner Philip Anschutz.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On September 11, 1996, Anschutz sold the combined company to the Union Pacific Railroad, creating the largest railroad network in the United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The Anschutz sale was partly in response to the earlier merger of Burlington Northern and Santa Fe which formed the large Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway (BNSF), Union Pacific's principal competitor in western U.S. railroading.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Both Union Pacific and BNSF have extensive freight operations in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Colorado's freight railroad network consists of 2,688 miles of Class I trackage.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] It is integral to the U.S. economy, being a critical artery for the movement of energy, agriculture, mining, and industrial commodities as well as general freight and manufactured products between the East and Midwest and the Pacific coast states.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In August 2014, Colorado began to issue driver licenses to aliens not lawfully in the United States who lived in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In September 2014, KCNC reported that 524 non-citizens were issued Colorado driver licenses that are normally issued to U.S. citizens living in Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The first institution of higher education in the Colorado Territory was the Colorado Seminary, opened on November 16, 1864, by the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The seminary closed in 1867 but reopened in 1880 as the University of Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] In 1870, the Bishop George Maxwell Randall of the Episcopal Church's Missionary District of Colorado and Parts Adjacent opened the first of what become the Colorado University Schools which would include the Territorial School of Mines opened in 1873 and sold to the Colorado Territory in 1874.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] These schools were initially run by the Episcopal Church.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] An 1861 territorial act called for the creation of a public university in Boulder, though it would not be until 1876 that the University of Colorado was founded.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The 1876 act also renamed Territorial School of Mines as the Colorado School of Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] An 1870 territorial act created the Agricultural College of Colorado which opened in 1879.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The college was renamed the Colorado State College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts in 1935, and became Colorado State University in 1957.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The first Catholic college in Colorado was the Jesuit Sacred Heart College, which was founded in New Mexico in 1877, moved to Morrison in 1884, and to Denver in 1887.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The college was renamed Regis College in 1921 and Regis University in 1991.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1924, armed students patrolled the campus after a burning cross was found, the climax of tensions between Regis College and the locally-powerful Ku Klux Klan.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Following a 1950 assessment by the Service Academy Board, it was determined that there was a need to supplement the U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Military and Naval Academies with a third school that would provide commissioned officers for the newly independent Air Force.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1954, President Dwight Eisenhower signed a law that moved for the creation of a U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] Later that year, Colorado Springs was selected to host the new institution.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] From its establishment in 1955, until the construction of appropriate facilities in Colorado Springs was completed and opened in 1958, the Air Force Academy operated out of Lowry Air Force Base in Denver.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] With the opening of the Colorado Springs facility, the cadets moved to the new campus, though not in the full-kit march that some urban and campus legends suggest.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The first class of Space Force officers from the Air Force Academy commissioned on April 18, 2020.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The two Native American reservations remaining in Colorado are the Southern Ute Indian Reservation (1873; Ute dialect: *Kapuuta-wa Moghwachi Núuchi-u*) and Ute Mountain Ute Indian Reservation (1940; Ute dialect: *Wʉgama Núuchi*).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p02] The two abolished Indian reservations in Colorado were the Cheyenne and Arapaho Indian Reservation (1851–1870) and Ute Indian Reservation (1855–1873).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p03] Colorado has five major professional sports leagues, all based in the Denver metropolitan area.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p03] Colorado is the least populous state with a franchise in each of the major professional sports leagues.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p03] The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb is a major hill climbing motor race held on the Pikes Peak Highway.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p03] The Cherry Hills Country Club has hosted several professional golf tournaments, including the U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p03] Women's Open, PGA Championship and BMW Championship.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-p03] The following universities and colleges participate in the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division I.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The **Colorado School of Mines** (**Mines**) is a public research university in Golden, Colorado, United States.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Founded in 1874, the school offers both undergraduate and graduate degrees in engineering, science, and mathematics, with a focus on energy and the environment.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] While Mines does offer undergraduate minor programs in the humanities, arts, and social sciences, it only offers degree programs in STEM fields, with the exception of economics.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In the fall 2025 semester, the school enrolled 8,247 students, including 6,371 undergraduate and 1,876 graduate students.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] It is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Golden, Colorado, established in 1859 as Golden City, served as a supply center for miners and settlers in the area.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Randall of Massachusetts arrived in the territory and, seeing a need for higher education facilities in the area, began planning for a university which would include a school of mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1870, he opened the Jarvis Hall Collegiate School in the central building of the Colorado University Schools campus just south of the town of Golden, accompanied it with Matthews Hall divinity school in 1872, and in 1873 the School of Mines opened under the auspices of the Episcopal Church.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1874 the School of Mines, supported by the territorial government since efforts began in 1870, was acquired by the territory and has been a state institution since 1876 when Colorado attained statehood.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Tuition was originally free to residents of Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1878, Jarvis Hall's main building and Matthews Hall were both destroyed by fires in the span of two days.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The School of Mines building was the only structure of the complex left standing.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Following the fires, the School of Mines enrollment grew, consisting of prospectors and mine owners.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] A school library was established with $250, and a gymnasium was built to support the growing student body.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The school's fight song, "The Mining Engineer", the first two verses of which are still sung today, was established on campus by 1885.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Following the 1880s, the School of Mines transitioned to become a 4-year university, removing its assaying certificate program.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Around this time, silver and blue began to be seen as the official school colors.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1894, Engineering Hall was completed.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] As the oldest building on campus, Engineering Hall originally housed the physics and drafting departments, but now houses the Division of Economics and Business.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The following year, the CSM Alumni Association was founded with members wearing the first instance of the school's Reuleaux triangle symbol.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1898, Florence Caldwell became the first female graduate of the School of Mines, earning a Civil Engineering Degree.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] At the turn of the century, the School of Mines officially changed its name to the Colorado School of Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] This marked the start of a long period of investment into Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1905, Simon Guggenheim donated $80,000 for the construction of Guggenheim Hall, which serves as the school's administration building.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] On nearby Mount Zion, student Herbert Everest designed a large M made out of rocks for his senior thesis, which was constructed by 20 faculty and 250 students.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Zion, the first experimental mine owned by the Colorado School of Mines was opened.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Known as the School Tunnel, it served to train mining engineers until 1921, when the Edgar Mine was purchased and the original School Tunnel was abandoned.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1919, tensions between the Colorado School of Mines and the University of Denver resulted in Colorado Governor Oliver Shoup threatening intervention after students from Mines held DU students and local news reporter Bill Bliss hostage in Golden.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] During World War II, Mines was one of 227 universities that participated in the Army Specialized Training Program by the War Department.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The program focused on training students in practical engineering skills for military service.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In August 2007, a new student recreation center was completed.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 2008, the school finished expanding its main computer center, the Center for Technology and Learning Media (CTLM).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 2014, CoorsTek granted a $27 million investment to the university, leading to the 2017 opening of the CoorsTek Center for Applied Science and Engineering, a multi-disciplinary building on campus dedicated to both academic and research activities.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Since 1964, the Colorado School of Mines has hosted the annual oil shale symposium, one of the most important international oil shale conferences.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Although the series of symposia stopped after 1992, the tradition was restored in 2006.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Colorado School of Mines is located to the southwest of Golden's downtown, bordered by U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The campus spans 373 acres (1.51 km2), and includes over a dozen academic and research buildings, indoor and outdoor athletic facilities, two student centers, a library, eight residential halls, and administration buildings.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Additionally, the campus hosts a research building for the United States Geological Survey, housing the National Earthquake Information Center.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Colorado School of Mines also operates the free admission Mines Museum of Earth Science, which displays rock and mineral specimens collected from Colorado's numerous mining districts, as well as around the world.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Notable objects in the collection include one of the "Goodwill" Apollo 17 lunar samples and the Miss Colorado crown.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Labriola Innovation District, composed of McNeil Hall, Aramco xWorks, and the Labriola Innovation Hub (InnoHub), was opened in early 2024.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Named after Frank and Mary Labriola, the InnoHub's 37,000 square feet and supporting buildings host the capstone design program, student design competition teams, and students' entrepreneurial and personal endeavors.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The InnoHub also consists of a machine shop, woodworking shop, composite workshop, electronics lab, tool rental center, additive manufacturing lab, and open-build space for student use.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] McNeil Hall contains classrooms dedicated to cornerstone and capstone design classes, as well as a large parking structure.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Mines Police Department, Lock Smith, Environmental Health and Safety, and Parking Services are also based on the first floor.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Beck Venture Center provides business mentorship and support for students and faculty to build businesses.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Multiple venture capitalists, angel investors, and engineering consultants maintain offices in the Venture Center to support the campus business ecosystem.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Mines, through the Beck Venture Center, is one of ten members of the western division of the National Science Foundation's Innovation Corps Program, which provides students and faculty with grants to pursue their inventions.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Edgar Experimental Mine is the primary educational mine owned by Mines in Idaho Springs.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The mine was originally a silver and gold mine founded in 1870 by the Big Five Mining Company.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] It was acquired by Mines in 1921 after Big Five declared bankruptcy.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Edgar Mine is primarily used to train mining engineers, although it is also used by various state and federal agencies to develop a wide range of products and techniques, including the U.S.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Army's tunnel detection program, which built one of the mine's two portals.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The mine features a fully operational mine railway, internet system, and classroom.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 2023, the FreePort-McMoRan Foundation gave $1 million to modernize Edgar Mine.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The USGS maintains multiple buildings and centers co-located on the Mines campus.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Federal Geologic Hazards Science Center, which includes the National Earthquake Information Center, Landslide Hazards Program, and Geomagnetism Program all are based on the main Mines campus.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 2023, federal, state, local, and university representatives broke ground on a new 190,000 sqft USGS Energy and Mineral Research Facility on the Mines campus.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] This building will house the USGS Geology, Geophysics, and Geochemistry Science Center as well as the Central Energy Resources Science Center.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Mines Museum of Earth and Science is a free museum located on the Mines campus with a collection of over 40,000 rocks, minerals, fossils, gems, and other earth-science related objects.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The museum's collection includes the Miss Colorado crown, which has multiple hand-carved amethyst state flowers, diamond, topaz, emerald, and ruby gemstones.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] It also includes two moon rocks: One of the State of Colorado's goodwill moon rocks, collected on the Apollo 17 mission, and one collected during the Apollo 11 mission.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Clear Creek Athletics Complex hosts facilities for Mines' varsity sports teams north of campus.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Softball Field, Jim Darden [Baseball] Field, Stermole Track & Field Complex, Stermole Soccer Stadium, and Alumni Field at Marv Kay Stadium.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Marv Kay Stadium was built in 2015 on the site of the historical Campbell Field.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Since 2015, additions have raised the capacity of the stadium, adding a permanent beer garden, standing room, and kids' zone in the west endzone.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Marv Kay stadium also contains practice facilities for teams at the Clear Creek Athletic Complex, including a varsity weight room, sports medicine offices, hydrotherapy center, equipment rooms, event center, and an auditorium.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Colorado School of Mines offers bachelor of science, master of science, professional master, and doctoral degrees, as well as postgraduate professional certifications.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The University is accredited by the Higher Learning Commission and the Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] All of Mines' programs are in STEM fields.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Mines offers 20 undergraduate degree programs, 100 graduate degree programs, and 30 postgraduate certificate programs.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Mines founded the world's first geophysics department in 1926 in response to the oil and mining industry's need for dedicated geophysical engineers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Additionally, Mines founded the world's first graduate program in space resources in the 2018 fall semester, offering both master's and PhD degrees.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Thorson First-Year Honors program replaces two freshman-level classes with Thorson-specific classes that emphasize the intersections of STEM and the humanities.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Students apply to the Thorson Honors program before beginning their freshman year at Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Each cohort of Thorson Scholars is split into seminar sessions led by interdisciplinary faculty teams that dive into critical thinking, design, communication, and ethical problem solving.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Thorson Honors students who are also approved for the Mines Study Abroad Program are given the opportunity to study in Antibes, France for their first semester.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Grandey First-Year Honors program uses a leadership lens and a maker mindset to educate its scholars in principles of problem solving, team communication, and project management.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Similar to the Thorson First-Year Honors Program, the Grandey Honors Program replaces two freshmen-level classes with small seminar classes led by a rotating team of expert faculty.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The McBride Honors Program in Public Affairs integrates the liberal arts with science and engineering.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Accepting about 40 students per year, the McBride Honors Program places a high emphasis on internships, particularly in public policy, industry, and the non-profit sector.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] To graduate with McBride Honors, scholars must complete a series of specialty classes as well as a self-designed practicum.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Past practica have included studying abroad, landscape painting, and making documentaries.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Practicum funding is typically provided by the scholar and program aid, depending on the scholar's needs.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Harvey Scholars program attracts students with a passion for service.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Programming includes luncheons with donors Hugh and Michelle Harvey, community-wide service activities, off-campus retreats, and small group dinners.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] A Harvey Scholarship covers full tuition and mandatory fees for eight semesters at Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] It also includes travel and enrichment grants to support study abroad programs, research pursuits, and professional development.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Vanguard and Caldwell Communities of Scholars are for highly motivated female students who embody leadership skills and a desire to improve the world through science, technology, engineering and mathematics.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] These service leadership programs develop transformational leaders through professional development, community service, and academic success opportunities over the course of four years.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] As members of the Vanguard and Caldwell communities, scholars benefit from vertically integrated support within the cohort, access to women faculty and campus leadership, in addition to financial assistance.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Caldwell students receive a full tuition scholarship and are identified as students who demonstrate a commitment to the legacy and ideals of Florence Caldwell.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Vanguard scholars receive a partial scholarship and are identified as students who will lead the way in making advances in STEM for society upon graduation.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Mines Undergraduate Research Fellowship Program provides funding for full-time undergraduate students to collaborate with campus researchers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] This provides students with an opportunity to participate in research projects under the mentorship of Mines faculty in every field represented at Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Some past research MURF students have contributed to includes research on Particle Physics, Explosives Engineering, and Oceanography.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Every undergraduate must complete one or more field sessions.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Field session is designed to expose students to practical skills in their discipline and provide experience graduates can lean on in their careers.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Typically, field sessions are offered in the summer, although some departments offer field sessions during the academic year.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Field session topics depend on the students interests and major.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Earth science students go on trips to survey and conduct research, while engineering students may complete a co-op, build semiconductors, or operate a chemical plant.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] For freshmen entering Fall 2021, Colorado School of Mines received 12,022 applications, accepted 6,838 (56.9%) and enrolled 1,449 (12.1% of those who applied).
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The middle 50% range of SAT scores for the enrolled freshmen was 650–720 for evidence-based reading, and 660–750 for math, while the ACT Composite range was 29–33.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Of the incoming class, 32.7% were women.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Freshmen students at Colorado School of Mines are expected (but not required) to participate in the M Climb during orientation week.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] During this climb, students carry a ten-pound rock up Mt.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Before ascending up the mountain, students are given colored hard-hats, which are spray-painted by members of the Blue Key Honor Society.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Along the climb, other students encourage the new students with water balloons, silly string, and lead the new students in learning the Mines' fight song.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] At the top of the mountain, students place their rock on the "M," a large sign made of rocks in the shape of Mines' M logo, and paint the M white using whitewash.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] On graduation, seniors are invited to take a rock from the M as a keepsake of their time at Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Beginning in 1934, Mines students have celebrated Engineering Days during the spring semester.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] During E-Days, classes are canceled and students attend a variety of events beginning with the ore cart pull.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Students take turns pulling an ore cart down 7.5 miles of Colfax Avenue to the state capitol building, where the governor of Colorado officially declares the start of E-Days.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] E-Days continues with field events, tech demos, concerts, comedians, manual mining competitions, and a trebuchet contest.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The next morning, teams race cardboard boats down Clear Creek, competing to see which team sails the farthest before sinking.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] A carnival is held during the day and the Formula SAE club hosts a car show.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The tradition of awarding silver diplomas was started in 1934 by Charles Hull, an Instrument Designer at Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Since then, every graduate receives a silver diploma upon graduation from Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 1935, President Herbert Hoover, who was a guest at the commencement ceremonies, was awarded an honorary Doctorate of Engineering for his contribution in translating *De re metallica* from Latin to English.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In the 1930s, a Golden local began to bring his burro to football games.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The burro quickly became the school mascot, now known as "Blaster the Burro".
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Blaster is represented by two separate burros, both racing burros from Idaho Springs, Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Both are known as Blaster while at Mines.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Around 1890 as a celebration of graduation, graduates of Mines received their "Engineer's" hat.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] These hats were worn by engineers while working underground, and whenever a visitor to a mine wanted to talk to the engineer, they were told to go find the guy in the funny hat.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Today, graduates receive one of two versions of the Engineer's hat, to be signed and branded upon graduation.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] Colorado School of Mines was ranked best NCAA DII school in the U.S. for student-athletes, according to Next College Student Athlete's 2025 NCSA Power Rankings.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The NCSA Power Rankings recognize the best colleges and universities in the U.S. for student-athletes.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In 2022, the Orediggers won their third national title in men's cross country, posting the largest margin of victory in meet history with 143-points.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] In December 2022, Oredigger football played in their first NCAA Division II national championship in McKinney, Texas, and lost to Ferris State 41-14.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] There are over 38,000 Colorado School of Mines Alumni working in various sectors, including engineering, entrepreneurial, corporate, medical, military, research, and public service positions.
[src:cowboy-jones/colorado-school-of-mines] The Colorado School of Mines Foundation supports alumni "M-Clubs", interest groups, and events across the United States and internationally.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] Born August 23, 1874, in Golden, Colorado Territory, Jones pitched collegiately for the Colorado School of Mines in 1894-1895.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] He has a known college record of 5-1 with 1 no decision, and 1 save if such a statistic had been kept, pitching 65 innings.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] This includes a 16-strikeout game against the University of Colorado at Golden on May 4, 1895 and an 11-strikeout performance against CU at Boulder on May 25, 1895.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] Jones began his professional career in 1896 with the Pueblo Rovers of the Colorado State League and made his major league debut on June 24, 1898 with the Cleveland Spiders.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] Jones was the first player born in Colorado to play in the major leagues, and the only one who played in the 19th century.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] In 1899, the Spiders' owners transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including Jones, to the St.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] Jones pitched three seasons for the Perfectos, who were renamed the Cardinals in 1899.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] Johnson played with the Cardinals through the 1901 season and continued to play minor league baseball until 1915, when he retired at age 41 and settled in the town of his birth, Golden, Colorado.
[src:cowboy-jones/cowboy-jones] Jones died in Inglewood, California on February 9, 1958.
